@page "/"

<PageTitle>BLite WASM Demo</PageTitle>

<h1>BLite WASM Demo</h1>

<p>
    This sample application demonstrates <strong>BLite</strong> running entirely in the browser
    via .NET WebAssembly. All data is stored locally using
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/IndexedDB_API" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IndexedDB</a>
    or
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/File_System_API/Origin_private_file_system" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OPFS</a>
    — no server required.
</p>

<p>
    Navigate to the <a href="/counter">Counter</a> page to try the persistent counter.
    Increment or decrement the counter, then reload the page — the value is restored from
    the BLite database stored in your browser.
</p>

<h2>What is BLite?</h2>
<p>
    BLite is an embedded, document-oriented database for .NET. In browser contexts it uses
    <code>BLite.Wasm</code>, which provides OPFS and IndexedDB storage backends through
    <code>[JSImport]</code> interop.
</p>

<h2>Quick-start</h2>
<pre><code>// In Program.cs of a Blazor WASM app:
builder.Services.AddBLiteWasm("my-database");

// Anywhere you need the engine:
@@inject BLiteEngine Engine

var doc = Engine.CreateDocument(["name", "score"],
    b =&gt; b.AddString("name", "Alice").AddInt32("score", 42));

await Engine.InsertAsync("players", doc);
</code></pre>
